  "text": "Surprisingly, [CITATION_1] found that the two hot residues, D898 and D900, with the greatest effect on ⌬ V 0.5 in the electrophysiological assay of Ca 2 ϩ dependence, also have a large inhibitory effect on 45 Ca 2 ϩ binding to the COOH-terminal 240 residues of the mSlo region, 50% and 51%, respectively, as measured for single alanine mutants of these residues (see Fig. 8 A of Bao et al., 2004, in this issue) . Four other \"cold/ medium\" residues that have little effect on ⌬ V 0.5 , also have a small effect on the 45 Ca 2 ϩ signal ( Ͻ 30%). However, spoiling the correlation, alanine mutation of an anomalous residue, D899, that has practically no effect on ⌬ V 0.5 , does have a rather large inhibitory effect (55%) on the 45 Ca 2 ϩ -binding signal. Double alanine mutations of pairs of residues, D898/D900 and D899/ D901, tend to reinforce these trends. Both of these latter double mutants inhibit the 45 Ca 2 ϩ -binding signal in the range of 73-80%.",
